<item>
  <title>MongoDB Host Access from Jupyter</title>
  <dc:creator>Ivan Ogasawara</dc:creator>
  <link>https://example.com/posts/mongodb-host-access/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ 




<p>Some students have had trouble connecting to their MongoDB instance from a notebook after moving to the current platform. The most common reason is that the new platform uses a different network configuration than the previous one.</p>
<div class="callout callout-style-default callout-important callout-titled">
<div class="callout-header d-flex align-content-center">
<div class="callout-icon-container">
<i class="callout-icon"></i>
</div>
<div class="callout-title-container flex-fill">
<span class="screen-reader-only">Important</span>Short Version
</div>
</div>
<div class="callout-body-container callout-body">
<p>Do not connect to <code>localhost</code>. Use the MongoDB host address provided by the platform.</p>
</div>
</div>
<section id="find-the-mongodb-host" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="find-the-mongodb-host">Find the MongoDB Host</h2>
<p>In the platform, click the <strong>Jupyter</strong> button.</p>
<p><img src="https://example.com/posts/mongodb-host-access/images/wqu-jupyter-menu.png" class="img-fluid" alt="The Jupyter button in the WQU platform interface."></p>
<p>This opens a pop-up with the Jupyter and MongoDB connection details. Copy the MongoDB IP address shown there.</p>
<p>In your notebook, store that address in a variable. For example, an IP address usually looks like four numbers separated by dots:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb1" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode python code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb1-1">host <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"192.168.1.25"</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>Use the actual MongoDB IP address from your platform pop-up, not the example above. If you want more background on what IP addresses are, see the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IP_address">Wikipedia page about IP addresses</a>.</p>
<p>Then use the <code>host</code> variable when you create the MongoDB client:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb2" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode python code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb2-1"><span class="im" style="color: #00769E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">from</span> pymongo <span class="im" style="color: #00769E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">import</span> MongoClient</span>
<span id="cb2-2"></span>
<span id="cb2-3">client <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> MongoClient(host<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span>host, port<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span><span class="dv" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">27017</span>)</span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>Using a variable makes the notebook easier to update. If the IP address changes later, you only need to update the <code>host</code> value in one place.</p>
</section>
<section id="common-error-connecting-to-localhost" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="common-error-connecting-to-localhost">Common Error: Connecting to Localhost</h2>
<p>If you see an error like this, your code is trying to connect to <code>localhost</code>:</p>
<pre class="text"><code>ServerSelectionTimeoutError: localhost:27017: [Errno 111] Connection refused</code></pre>
<p>The important part is <code>localhost:27017</code>. That means the notebook is looking for MongoDB on the notebook machine itself, not on the MongoDB host provided by the platform.</p>
<p>This usually happens when the code still looks like this:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb4" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode python code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb4-1">client <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> MongoClient(host<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span><span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"localhost"</span>, port<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span><span class="dv" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">27017</span>)</span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>Change it to:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb5" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode python code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb5-1">client <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> MongoClient(host<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span>host, port<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span><span class="dv" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">27017</span>)</span></code></pre></div></div>
</section>
<section id="why-hosthost-is-correct" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="why-hosthost-is-correct">Why <code>host=host</code> Is Correct</h2>
<p>The expression <code>host=host</code> can look confusing at first because the same word appears twice.</p>
<p>In this line:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb6" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode python code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb6-1">client <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> MongoClient(host<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span>host, port<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span><span class="dv" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">27017</span>)</span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>The first <code>host</code> is the parameter name expected by <code>MongoClient</code>.</p>
<p>The second <code>host</code> is the variable you created earlier:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb7" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode python code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb7-1">host <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> <span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"your-mongodb-ip-address"</span></span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>So <code>host=host</code> means: pass the value stored in the <code>host</code> variable to the <code>host</code> parameter.</p>
</section>
<section id="another-common-mistake-using-host-as-text" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="another-common-mistake-using-host-as-text">Another Common Mistake: Using <code>"host"</code> as Text</h2>
<p>If your error message mentions something like <code>host:27017</code>, check whether your code uses quotation marks around <code>host</code>:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb8" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode python code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb8-1">client <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> MongoClient(host<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span><span class="st" style="color: #20794D;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">"host"</span>, port<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span><span class="dv" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">27017</span>)</span></code></pre></div></div>
<p>That is different from <code>host=host</code>.</p>
<p><code>"host"</code> is just the literal text <code>host</code>. Python will not replace it with your variable value.</p>
<p>Use this instead:</p>
<div class="code-copy-outer-scaffold"><div class="sourceCode" id="cb9" style="background: #f1f3f5;"><pre class="sourceCode python code-with-copy"><code class="sourceCode python"><span id="cb9-1">client <span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span> MongoClient(host<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span>host, port<span class="op" style="color: #5E5E5E;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">=</span><span class="dv" style="color: #AD0000;
background-color: null;
font-style: inherit;">27017</span>)</span></code></pre></div></div>
</section>
<section id="how-to-read-the-error-message" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="how-to-read-the-error-message">How to Read the Error Message</h2>
<p>Error messages usually include useful clues. For MongoDB connection issues, look for the host and port in the message:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>localhost:27017</code> usually means the code is still using <code>localhost</code>.</li>
<li><code>host:27017</code> usually means the code is using the string <code>"host"</code> instead of the variable <code>host</code>.</li>
<li>A platform IP followed by <code>:27017</code> means the code is at least trying the intended host, so the next thing to check is whether the copied IP address is correct.</li>
</ul>
<p>The error type is also useful. <code>ServerSelectionTimeoutError</code> means the client could not reach a MongoDB server before the timeout. In this case, the cause is often the wrong host address.</p>
</section>
<section id="when-you-still-need-help" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="when-you-still-need-help">When You Still Need Help</h2>
<p>If you have checked the host value and still cannot connect, reach out to the support team or attend an Office Hours session. Include the exact error message and the connection code you are using, but do not share private credentials.</p>


</section>

 ]]></description>
